article.description:
George McCloud scored 26 points and Voshon Lenard
added seven of his 14 points in overtime as the Denver Nuggets beat Portland 109-106 on Saturday night, snapping the Trail Blazers' 12-game winning streak.
article.headline: McCloud, Nuggets finally stop Blazers

images.name: Howard, Juwon 020304 inline
images.caption: The Nuggets' Juwon Howard gets a good look in front of Rasheed Wallace, left, and Dale Davis.

article.linkText: Nuggets stop Trail Blazers' 12-game winning streak
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- The Denver Nuggets turned to veterans Tim Hardaway, George McCloud and Voshon Lenard to stop the surging Portland Trail Blazers. Hardaway came off the bench to hit two 3-pointers in the final 22 seconds of regulation, McCloud scored 26 points, and Lenard added seven of his 14 points in overtime as Denver beat Portland 109-106 Saturday night. The loss halted the Trail Blazers' winning streak at 12 games. "It's not that the streak is over, it's how we lost," Portland coach Maurice Cheeks said. "That's a dagger. "We had the game won three times and, for whatever reason, we come here and have to walk out with heavy hearts." Juwan Howard added 18 points and 12 rebounds for the Nuggets, who won their second straight. The key to Denver's comeback was Hardaway, whose 3-pointer with two seconds left tied the game and forced overtime. "Believe me, it's real hard when you're 35," Hardaway said of being called off the bench late in a game. "Just sitting there and then the coach calls your name." Denver coach Mike Evans had plenty of confidence in Hardaway. "He's the kind of guy you want in the game when the game is on the line," Evans said. "We've had a chance to really work on our end-of-the-game stuff, and he'd gotten more familiar with what we wanted to do off it." Scottie Pippen had 28 points and 10 rebounds, but missed a critical free throw with eight seconds left for the Trail Blazers. Rasheed Wallace added 26 points. A 3-pointer by Lenard and a short jumper by Hardaway gave the Nuggets a 102-97 lead with 3:35 left in overtime. Bonzi Wells, who scored 21 points, hit a jumper, but Howard countered with a basket that gave Denver a 104-99 lead. Pippen hit four straight free throws to tie the game at 104 with 1:01 left. Lenard hit two free throws for the Nuggets and, after Wells missed a jumper, Donnell Harvey sealed the victory by making two free throws with 6.1 seconds left. Leading by eight at the start of the fourth quarter, Portland's defense forced two shot-clock violations. After a driving layup by Pippen, Portland led 79-70. A free throw by Howard made it 88-84 with 1:55 left. The Nuggets erased a 91-84 deficit in the final 31 seconds to send the game into overtime. After Wallace converted a three-point play, Hardaway made a 3-pointer with 22 seconds left. After Pippen converted two free throws, McCloud hit a 3-pointer with 11 seconds left to cut the deficit to 94-92. Pippen made one of two free throws before Hardaway's 3-pointer with two seconds left tied the game at 95. "When he (Pippen) missed that free throw, I thought coming back is always possible," Hardaway said. "I just went down and hit the shot." Evans said: "Tim's been making shots like that his whole career." Portland used a 9-0 run to push its lead to 64-46 four minutes into the third quarter. After a 3-pointer by Derek Anderson, reserve James Posey hit two shots from beyond the arc. The Nuggets closed the quarter with an 11-3 run to get within 74-66. The Trail Blazers made 15 of their first 22 shots, including four of five from 3-point range, for an early 36-22 lead. Portland missed its first seven shots at the start of the second quarter. McCloud scored eight points and the Nuggets closed within 37-36. The Trail Blazers went on a 16-6 run and took a 53-42 halftime lead. Game notes
A snowstorm on Friday forced the Trail Blazers to alter their travel plans and fly into Denver early Saturday morning. ... Portland is 8-11 on the second night of back-to-back games. ... The Nuggets have hit at least one 3-pointer in 252 straight games.
